        "id": "e8e5bdc32a52a16f",
        "text": "Re-entry indicates the “re-introduction” of a distinction into a domain that is differentiated by the distinction itself. The term is derived from George Spencer Brown’s logical calculus [→Operation/Observation], a feature of which is that it is based exclusively on the operation of indication/distinction. Sys- tems theory interprets this operation as observation: something is indicated and at the same time distinguished from others things. The connections be- tween operations within one and the same system lead to the construction of ever more complex forms, until the point at which the calculus has reached a sufficient level of complexity. Then the system includes an operation that, in place of an external object, again indicates the system-constituting operation of indication/distinction,i.e., the same operation that the operation itself realizes."
